## Supabase rules

- **4-client split.** Pick the right one and never blur boundaries:
  - `src/supabase/client.ts` — browser (anon key, RLS-protected).
  - `src/supabase/server.ts` — Server Components, route handlers, server actions (anon key + user cookies).
  - `src/supabase/server-admin.ts` — service-role. MUST start with `import "server-only"`. Only for admin/cron paths after `isAdmin()` check.
  - `src/supabase/middleware.ts` — edge session refresh only.
- **RLS first, zod second.** Every table has RLS enabled. Re-validate every input server-side with zod even after the client validated.
- **No `.select('*')`.** Always list the columns you actually need — keeps payloads small and migrations safe.
- **Admin gating.** Use `isAdmin()` from `@/lib/auth/is-admin` for role checks. Gate at BOTH middleware and the (admin) layout — defense in depth.
- **Service role.** Never imported from any client/edge file. The `server-only` import will throw at build time if it leaks.

## Migrations

- Filename: `supabase/migrations/YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_<slug>.sql` (UTC timestamp, slug in kebab-case).
- Always: `alter table ... enable row level security;`
- Always idempotent: `create table if not exists`, `drop policy if exists ... ;` before `create policy`, `create index if not exists`.
- Explicit columns in DML; no `*`.
- Add a rollback note at the bottom of the file.
- Auto-update timestamp triggers belong inline in the same migration.

## Don'ts

- Don't use the service-role client to "fix" a missing RLS policy — write the policy.
- Don't call the admin client from a route handler before checking `isAdmin()`.
- Don't run raw SQL in app code; route it through Supabase types.

See `.agents/rules/supabase.md` and `.agents/rules/admin.md`.
